SIMPLE: defile
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Defile
<hw>De*file"</hw> <pr>(d⟦esl⟧*f⟦imac⟧l")</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Defiled</conjf>
<pr>(d⟦esl⟧*f⟦imac⟧ld")</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Defiling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>d⟦eacute⟧filer</ets>;
pref. <ets>d⟦eacute⟧-</ets>, for <ets>des-</ets> (L. <ets>dis-</ets>) +
<ets>file</ets> a row or line. See <er>File</er> a row.]</ety> <def>To
march off in a line, file by file; to file off.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Defile</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Defile
<hw>De*file"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>Same as
<er>Defilade</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Defile</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Defile
<hw>De*file"</hw> <pr>(d⟦esl⟧*f⟦imac⟧l" <it>or</it> d⟦emac⟧"f⟦imac⟧l;
277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>d⟦eacute⟧fil⟦eacute⟧</ets>,
fr. <ets>d⟦eacute⟧filer</ets> to defile.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Any
narrow passage or gorge in which troops can march only in a file, or
with a narrow front; a long, narrow pass between hills, rocks,
etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>The act of defilading a fortress,
or of raising the exterior works in order to protect the interior. See
<er>Defilade</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Defile</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Defile
<hw>De*file"</hw> <pr>(d⟦esl⟧*f⟦imac⟧l")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<ety>[OE. <ets>defoulen</ets>, <ets>-foilen</ets>, to tread down, OF.
<ets>defouler</ets>; <ets>de-</ets> + <ets>fouler</ets> to trample (see
<er>Full</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>), and OE. <ets>defoulen</ets> to foul
(influenced in form by the older verb <ets>defoilen</ets>). See
<er>File</er> to defile, <er>Foul</er>, <er>Defoul</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To make foul or impure; to make filthy; to dirty; to
befoul; to pollute.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They that touch pitch will be <qex>defiled</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To soil or sully; to tarnish, as reputation; to
taint.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He is . . . among the greatest prelates of this age, however his
character may be <qex>defiled</qex> by . . . dirty hands.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To injure in purity of character; to
corrupt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Defile</qex> not yourselves with the idols of Egypt.</q>
<rj><qau>Ezek. xx. 7.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To corrupt the chastity of; to debauch; to violate;
to rape.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The husband murder'd and the wife <qex>defiled</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To make ceremonially unclean; to pollute.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That which dieth of itself, or is torn with beasts, he shall not
eat to <qex>defile</qex> therewith.</q> <rj><qau>Lev. xxii.
8.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>defiled</ent>⟦br⟧
